entry.title: [mullet m2] Add address-line1 info when address field does not have it.
entry.content:
The goal of this CL is to give users more context about what they are

about to fill. In a scenario where an user clicks on a ZIP CODE

the label is their city name, it might not be clear what will

actually be filled.



To fix this, in the case where the triggering field is not already

ADDRESS_LINE1,2 or ADDRESS_HOME_ADDRESS (which is basically the combination ADDRESS_LINE1,2,3) and ADDRESS_HOME_STREET_ADDRESS,

we add ADDRESS_LINE1 as part of the granular filling label.



Another change in this CL is the fact that the separator "-" is

not its own label anymore. This is ok and is needed so that can

have the following formatting:



"fill address - erika-mann... 32" where:

label 1: fill address - erika-mann

label 2: 32



After talking to Dima, we are also going to do that same for first level

suggestions, so this CL also makes it easier to introduce that.

entry.content:
Refactor and fix the implementation for Display

Cutout Host support in a new flag-guarded implementation

in safe_area_insets_host_impl. This effectively deprecates the

DisplayCutoutHostImpl when the E2E Flag is enabled.



Adds safe_area_insets_host_impl class files, which

are activated when the DrawCutoutEdgeToEdge and

DrawEdgeToEdge are enabled.



The new implementation uses DocumentUserData to track the

viewport-fit value associated with each Blink frame. This

simplifies the problem of navigation within the same RFH

because the loaded UserData is independent of the previous

one so it can easily track the viewport-fit from those pages

separately.

entry.title: [AsyncSB] Introduce async_sb_checker in BrowserUrlLoaderThrottle
entry.content:
When async real time SB check is enabled, BULT will create two

UrlCheckerOnSB: one for sync check, and one for async check. The sync

check only performs local database check. It defers

WillProcessResponse if it is not yet completed. The async check, on

the other hand, performs real-time check. If BULT is ready to proceed

(sync check is completed and WillProcessResponse is called), but the

async check has not yet completed, it will be transferred to

AsyncCheckTracker to continue the check.



Below is a breakdown of the expected behavior:

Definition:

* Event A: Sync check is completed.

* Event B: Async check is completed.

* Event C: WillProcessResponse is called.

* defer: UrlLoader is deferred.

* transfer: Async checker is transferred to tracker.

Order of events and the expected behavior:

* A -> B -> C: no defer, no transfer.

* A -> C -> B: no defer, transfer.

* B -> A -> C: no defer, no transfer.

* B -> C -> A: defer, no transfer.

* C -> A -> B: defer, transfer.

* C -> B -> A: defer, no transfer.



Cases that the URL is dangerous:

If sync check returns dangerous:

* the async check will be canceled immediately if it is not

completed.

If async check returns dangerous:

* If it has not yet been transferred to tracker:

* the sync check will be canceled immediately.

* If it is transferred to tracker:

* The tracker may trigger a warning. This will be implemented in

a follow up CL.

entry.title: [ios] Avoid over-realisation when moving tabs to/from inactive
entry.content:
When moving tabs to/from the inactive Browser on startup, first

compute the set of all tabs to move (and possibly close in case

This allow to determine the index of the new active WebState

activated. Since the default Browser's WebStateListDelegate

force the realisation of WebState on activation, this prevents

over realisation in a pathological case (see bug).



As an optimisation, this allow to not create an empty batch

operation when there are no tabs to move.

entry.title: Protected Audiences: Fix Interest Group Cache Coherence
entry.content:
Currently, OnLoadInterestGroupsForOwner and

OnLoadInterestGroupsForOwnerOneCallback could

save outdated values to the cache because they do not check if the value

is outdated before saving it. The prior solution to this problem

(https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5039710)

was insufficient, because it does not address situations that can arise from interwoven invalidations and reads. For example:

1. Start Read

2. Invalidate (Join Interest group)

3. Start Read

4. Invalidate (Join Interest group)

5. Start Read

6. Read from 1 completes

7. Read from 3 completes

8. Read (gets invalidated cache data from the 3 Read).

9. Read 5 completes



Version the callbacks stored in InterestGroupCachingStorage.

entry.title: Refactor and fix CronetEngine ref logging
entry.content:
This CL addresses the following problems with the way we log the

CronetEngine ID:



- The ID is a `long` in CronetStatsLog (which makes sense since it's an

`int64` in the atom proto, but CronetLogger uses `int`.



- More importantly, the way the ID is computed using `Object#hashCode()`

is very wrong because this approach does not guarantee *at all* that

different CronetEngine instances will have different IDs. This may

sound far-fetched, but it's not: consider that, if the JVM decides to

construct a CronetEngine in the same memory location as another

CronetEngine that was destroyed earlier (which doesn't seem

far-fetched at all), then they will, in fact, end up with the same

hashCode, yet they are different instances.



In this CL the ID is generated at random while avoiding potentially

confusing special values, and the ID generation function is moved to the

CronetLogger abstract interface for easy reuse (our new atoms will have

plenty more IDs to fill in) and for easy faking in tests.

is required to support such format from what I understand.



Regarding the above issues, as Dolby Vision contents usually

encoded with H.264/5 codecs, then as long as device supports H.264/5 codec and `dv_bl_signal_compatibility_id` equals to 1,2,4 (HDR10,

SDR,HLG compatible), then a downgrade should be performed and let

these videos at least able to playback normally as H.264/5 codec

contents as long as developer `addSourceBuffer` with mimetype

looks like `hev1.2.4.L120.90` or `avc1.4d4015`.



Note that when `addSourceBuffer` with mimetype looks like `dvh1.08.07`,

then dolby vision contents will always be treated as dolby vision,

the playback may still fails as expected if browser doesn't

support dolby vision on the current platform.



For web developers, the logic will be something like below:



```

if (isTypeSupported('video/mp4;codecs="dvh1.08.07"')) {

if (use_rpu) {

// Should be success and rendered with RPU meta.

source.addSourceBuffer('video/mp4;codecs="dvh1.08.07"');

...

} else if (dvcc.dv_bl_signal_compatibility_id === 1 ||

dvcc.dv_bl_signal_compatibility_id === 2 ||

dvcc.dv_bl_signal_compatibility_id === 4) {

// Should be success and rendered without RPU meta as

// normal HLG/HDR10/SDR contents.

source.addSourceBuffer('video/mp4;codecs="hev1.2.4.L120.90"');

...

} else {

// Downgrade is not allowed, playback fails.

}

} else if (isTypeSupported('video/mp4;codecs="hev1.2.4.L120.90"')) {

if (dvcc.dv_bl_signal_compatibility_id === 1 ||

dvcc.dv_bl_signal_compatibility_id === 2 ||

dvcc.dv_bl_signal_compatibility_id === 4) {

// Should be success and rendered without RPU meta as

// normal HLG/HDR10/SDR contents.

source.addSourceBuffer('video/mp4;codecs="hev1.2.4.L120.90"');

...

} else {

// Downgrade is not allowed, playback fails.

}

} else {

// HEVC is not supported, playback fails.

}

```

entry.title: Reland "Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 440828a02e56dcecd43896676a0c765db907c3b9



The CL removed "legacy" from the possible values of the feature

parameter kAutofillParsingPatternActiveSource. This broke a bunch of

parsing tests, since they are parameterized by pattern source. This CL

fixes this (see patchset 1 -> latest) by excluding "legacy" in

builds without Autofill internal patterns.



Presumably, this didn't show up during the CQ because none of the bots

are using the internal patterns.



Original change's description:

> Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns

>

> A HeuristicSource describes a mechanism to get heuristic predictions,

> which is currently either ML or regexes. Due to pattern provider,

> which can provide different regex definitions, "regexes" is split

> further into different PatternSources.

>

> The active HeuristicSource defines the mechanism that's used to compute

> the fields' heuristic types used in production (the one that will

> influence the overall type used for filling).

>

> The non-active HeuristicSources are defined as the set of all available

> HeuristicSources, except the active HeuristicSource. The PatternSources

> among these non-active HeuristicSources are used to compute shadow predictions for the kAutofillParsingPatternProvider experiment.

>

> What exactly all available HeuristicSources are depends on build flags

> and feature flags, and this CL changes that definition.

>

> Generally:

> - HeuristicSource::kMachineLearning is only available when

> kAutofillModelPredictions is enabled.

> - HeuristicSource::kDefault, HeuristicSource::kExperimental and

> HeuristicSource::kNextGen are only available in Chrome branded builds

> when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

> - HeuristicSource::kLegacy is always available.

>

> This CL removes HeuristicSource::kLegacy from the available patterns in

> Chrome branded builds when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

> This is desirable for a few reasons:

> - Chrome branded builds with kAutofillParsingPatternProvider are not

> using the kLegacy patterns, not even for shadow metrics. They are

> intended to be lower-quality regexes for non-Chrome branded builds.

> - Since they are currently part of the non-active HeuristicSources,

> they take up additional computational resources during parsing.

>
